\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 All these explanations treat people as passive objects, recipients of outside influences, targets of the workings of eternal forces, compliant tools of outside agencies. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The actual story would have to allow for the everlasting conflict between progressives and conservatives, between the forward and the backward looking, between those who propose \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91let\u8217\'92s do something new\u8217\'92, and those who think \u8216\'91the old ways are best\u8217\'92, \u8216\'91lets improve\u8217\'92 vs. \u8216\'91If it ain\u8217\'92t broke, don\u8217\'92t fix it\u8217\'92.  No great shift in culture ever took place without such a contest.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The neolithic revolution that took our ancestors from hunting and gathering in small kinship-based bands to a settled, communal village life of subsistence agriculture was the greatest ever mass-destroyer of skills, cultures and languages in human history. No band of hunter gatherers can have simply given up all they knew and settled down to sedentary farming without engaging in a giant battle of ideas.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 To the author of Genesis, the neolithic revolution signified the fall of man: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91Cursed is the ground for thy sake; in sorrow shalt thou eat of it all the days of thy life. Thorns and thistles shall it bring forth to thee; and thou shalt eat of the herb of the field. In the sweat of thy face shalt thou eat bread.\u8217\'92\u8230\'85colin tudge: \u8216\'91farming in neolithic times was obviously harsh: the first farming peoples were less robust than the hunter-gatherers who had preceded them, and suffered nutritional, traumatic and infectious disorders that their forebears had been spared.\u8217\'92 }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 In this light it seems that the momentous change to agriculture as the basis of life can only have been driven by the spread of a powerful new ideology, necessarily in those days expressed in the form a new religion, propogated with, as Jacques Cauvin put it, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91messianic self-confience\u8217\'92.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ****As the archaeologists dug int John Taylor\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s gigantic ruined fort, which they were now able to date to the twenty-first century BCe, they uncovered a much earlier and smaller building under one corner, dating from nearly 2,000 years before that. Beneath this they found yet another sixteen levels of habitation, going right back to the beginning of the fifth millennium BCE, when they finally reached a \u8216\'91dune of clean sand\u8217\'92 on which had first been erected \u8216\'91a primitive chapel\u8217\'92, a little over ten feet square,constructed of sun-dried brick, with a votive pedestal facing the entrance and a recessed niche, perhaps for a sculptured image.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Mesopotamia acted as a kind of experimental laboratory for civilization, testing, often to destruction, many kinds of religion, from early personifications of natural forces to full-blown temple priesthood and even monotheism;from state planning to neo-liberal privatization. Primitive democracy, consultative monarcy, ruthless tyranny, expansive imperialism. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Sun dried brick demands constant maintenance if it is not to recycle itself back into the ground - it was lack of repair, not destruction, that crumbled most of the ancient cities of sumer into mounds of dust.  Shows the ideology of progress; the belief that it was both possible and desirable continually to improve on what had gone before, that the future could and should be better - and bigger- than the past. The divine power celebrated and honoured here was the epression, embodiment and personification of that idea: no less than the god or goddess of civilization.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 City names were written with a sign denoting \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91god\u8217\'92, a sign for then ame of the god, and the sign for \u8216\'91place\u8217\'92: nippur was written God.Enlil.Place}
